<DocsLayout title="Why Groundwork" description="The problem Groundwork solves, the bets it makes, and what it deliberately leaves out">
  <section class="gw-section">
    <div class="gw-width gw-prose">
      <h1 class="gw-heading-l">Why Groundwork</h1>
      <p>
        Groundwork is a small, opinionated design system for general web application development. This page
        is the longer answer to "what is this, why does it exist, and what is not in scope" — the kind of
        context worth reading once before reaching for a component.
      </p>

      <h2 class="gw-heading-m">The problem</h2>
      <p>
        Every new project starts with the same waste: picking colours, arguing about spacing, reinventing
        form validation UX, forgetting accessible labels, choosing between 14px and 15px for secondary text.
        These are not interesting decisions. They are tax.
      </p>
      <p>
        Design systems exist to eliminate this tax, but most of them optimise for the wrong thing. They
        optimise for flexibility — every possible option, so you can build anything. The result is hundreds
        of utility classes, dozens of button variants, and teams that still ship inconsistent UIs because
        the system said "here are your options" instead of "here is the answer."
      </p>
      <p>
        GOV.UK's design system works because it does the opposite. It makes the decisions for you. One
        button style. One input pattern. One way to handle errors. The constraints are not limitations —
        they are the product. You stop thinking about UI decisions and start thinking about the thing you
        are actually building.
      </p>
      <p>Groundwork is that philosophy applied to general web application development.</p>

      <h2 class="gw-heading-m">The bet</h2>
      <p>
        The bet is that a small, closed, opinionated system will produce better outcomes than a large,
        flexible one. Specifically:
      </p>
      <ul class="gw-list">
        <li>
          <strong>A closed token set</strong> (12 spacing values, 7 type sizes, semantic-only colours)
          eliminates visual drift across pages and over time. You cannot introduce
          <code class="gw-mono">padding: 13px</code> because 13 does not exist.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>React components with restrictive APIs</strong> (required labels, no className override,
          variant unions instead of string props) turn documentation into compiler errors. You do not need
          to remember the rules — the types enforce them.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Form patterns as the core feature</strong> (Field wrapper, error summary, width hints,
          check-your-answers) cover the 80% case for application UI. Most apps are forms. Do forms
          exceptionally well and everything else is incremental.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Two-tier tokens</strong> (private primitives → public semantic) make re-theming a
          primitive swap rather than a component-by-component restyle, while keeping the public API small
          enough to hold in your head.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="gw-heading-m">What Groundwork is not</h2>
      <ul class="gw-list">
        <li>
          <strong>Not a component mega-library.</strong> Roughly seventeen components. If you need a date
          range picker or a drag-and-drop kanban board, build it on top or use something else.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Not framework-agnostic.</strong> The CSS layer is generic. The component layer is React.
          There are no Web Component wrappers, no Vue bindings, no Svelte port.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Not a design tool integration.</strong> No Figma plugin, no design-to-code pipeline.
          Tokens live in JSON, generate CSS, and that is the workflow.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Not a CSS framework.</strong> There is no utility class system. Layout is handled by four
          primitives (stack, cluster, prose, grid); the rest is component-level.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="gw-heading-m">Success criteria</h2>
      <p>Groundwork succeeds when:</p>
      <ol class="gw-list">
        <li>Starting a new application's UI takes minutes, not hours.</li>
        <li>
          The second project built with Groundwork looks consistent with the first without any manual
          effort.
        </li>
        <li>
          Accessibility basics (labels, focus, error messaging, colour independence) are impossible to skip,
          not just encouraged.
        </li>
        <li>
          Re-theming for a different visual identity requires changing a handful of primitive values, not
          auditing every component.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>It fails if:</p>
      <ol class="gw-list">
        <li>
          The token set or component count grows to the point where you need to search documentation to
          find the right option.
        </li>
        <li>
          The restrictive API creates so much friction that consumers bypass it with escape hatches on every
          other component.
        </li>
        <li>It becomes a project about a design system rather than a tool for building other projects.</li>
      </ol>

